WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.800 --> 00:00:04.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:16.750 --> 00:00:18.050
&gt;&gt; Anya Creightney: Hi everyone.

00:00:18.050 --> 00:00:21.170
Thanks for joining us this
afternoon to celebrate the birthday

00:00:21.170 --> 00:00:24.150
of a very special writer,
Elizabeth Bishop.

00:00:24.150 --> 00:00:26.460
My name is Anya Creightney.

00:00:26.460 --> 00:00:27.760
Come on in.

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:30.710
And I'm the Program Specialist for
the Poetry and Literature Center

00:00:30.710 --> 00:00:32.490
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:32.490 --> 00:00:35.230
I'm also a proud partner in
this series, representing

00:00:35.230 --> 00:00:36.820
and celebrating the careers of many

00:00:36.820 --> 00:00:40.390
of our most valuable
literary voices.

00:00:40.390 --> 00:00:43.300
Elizabeth Bishop is one of
those writers who shapes

00:00:43.300 --> 00:00:46.330
and contours our world
as though it were putty.

00:00:46.330 --> 00:00:51.590
Her poetics are indelicate, yet
solid, earthen, yet water bound,

00:00:51.590 --> 00:00:54.730
slippery, yet confidentially
precise.

00:00:54.730 --> 00:00:57.250
She is a poet with a
keen, unwavering eye.

00:00:57.250 --> 00:01:01.110
And lucky for us, she found
no scene too domestic,

00:01:01.110 --> 00:01:04.920
no folk too ordinary,
no object too small.

00:01:04.920 --> 00:01:09.510
So, perhaps it gives you comfort,
as it does many, to let Bishop,

00:01:09.510 --> 00:01:12.760
quiet and substantial as
she was, study the boundary

00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:15.470
between the external
and the internal,

00:01:15.470 --> 00:01:18.740
the boundary between
border and flux.

00:01:18.740 --> 00:01:20.760
Absolutely, it is with
this excitement

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:24.660
that I welcome poets Jennifer
Atkinson and Vijay Seshadri.

00:01:24.660 --> 00:01:29.010
Both of whom will help us better
understand Bishop and her poetics.

00:01:29.010 --> 00:01:31.660
Each poet will lecture for
approximately twenty minutes.

00:01:31.660 --> 00:01:35.420
And both will conclude by sharing
excerpts of their own work.

00:01:35.420 --> 00:01:39.070 position:56%
And I should note that Vijay is
going to share poems, Bishops poems,

00:01:39.070 --> 00:01:42.130
here today and then read
poems of his conclusion.

00:01:42.130 --> 00:01:44.880
Jennifer Atkinson is the author
of five poetry collections.

00:01:44.880 --> 00:01:47.790
The most recent, "The Thinking
Eye," looks at the syntax

00:01:47.790 --> 00:01:50.980
of our evolving world, paying
close attention to landscape,

00:01:50.980 --> 00:01:53.520
ecology, myth and memory.

00:01:53.520 --> 00:01:56.120
She is a professor in
the BFA and MFA programs

00:01:56.120 --> 00:01:58.070
at George Mason University.

00:01:58.070 --> 00:02:01.190
Vijay Seshadri is the
author of three collections.

00:02:01.190 --> 00:02:03.410
The most recent of which
of the three selections,

00:02:03.410 --> 00:02:06.230
won the Pulitzer Prize
for Poetry in 2014.

00:02:06.230 --> 00:02:12.180
He is a professor and the Michele
Tolela Myers Chair in Writing

00:02:12.180 --> 00:02:15.640
at Sarah Lawrence University
in Yonkers, New York.

00:02:15.640 --> 00:02:18.880 position:56%
Lastly, our event will conclude with
a tabletop presentation of items,

00:02:18.880 --> 00:02:22.850
that you see here to my left, from
the Library's Bishop collection.

00:02:22.850 --> 00:02:25.210
And Mark Manivong here,
sitting here in the front row,

00:02:25.210 --> 00:02:27.570
is a curator from the Rare
and Special Book Division.

00:02:27.570 --> 00:02:30.200
And he will invite you all,
at the very end of the event,

00:02:30.200 --> 00:02:32.910
to take a look at the
items presented here.

00:02:32.910 --> 00:02:36.500
So, before I turn it over to
our poets here, let me ask you

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:38.200
to turn off your cell
phones or anything

00:02:38.200 --> 00:02:41.650
that could interfere
with the reading today.

00:02:41.650 --> 00:02:43.560 position:56%
And let me also say one little thing

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:45.070
about the Poetry and
Literature Center.

00:02:45.070 --> 00:02:48.060
We are the home of the Poet
Laureate Consultant in Poetry,

00:02:48.060 --> 00:02:49.840
who currently is Juan
Felipe Herrera.

00:02:49.840 --> 00:02:52.600
And we put on thirty
to forty programs,

00:02:52.600 --> 00:02:54.450
just like this one, per year.

00:02:54.450 --> 00:02:57.020
To find out more about
