00:02:57.020 --> 00:02:58.420
please join our mailing list.

00:02:58.420 --> 00:02:59.980
And you can do so at
the back of the room.

00:02:59.980 --> 00:03:02.390
There is a clipboard
you can fill out.

00:03:02.390 --> 00:03:05.730
And without further ado, let
me turn it over to our poets,

00:03:05.730 --> 00:03:08.290
first of whom is Jennifer Atkinson.

00:03:09.510 --> 00:03:15.440
[ Applause ]

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:17.330
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Atkinson:
Thanks everyone for coming.

00:03:17.330 --> 00:03:21.770
And thank you Anya
and Matt and Mark.

00:03:21.770 --> 00:03:23.220
This stuff is amazing.

00:03:23.220 --> 00:03:28.580
You have to see this, if
you haven't looked yet.

00:03:28.580 --> 00:03:34.420
So, I'm going to talk a little
bit and then read a few, like,

00:03:34.420 --> 00:03:36.470
three, I think, of my poems.

00:03:36.470 --> 00:03:40.340
And I'm going to concentrate on
-- it was very hard to pick, like,

00:03:40.340 --> 00:03:44.430
which Bishop poem to
read, but to think about.

00:03:44.430 --> 00:03:47.670
But I picked in the end
a poem called "Poem."

00:03:47.670 --> 00:03:53.260
Well, I'm going to start.

00:03:53.260 --> 00:03:56.240
Okay, I'll start -- you know,

00:03:56.240 --> 00:03:59.810
I'm sort of changing my mind
right now, while I talk to you.

00:03:59.810 --> 00:04:02.150
But no, I'm going to
go ahead with this.

00:04:02.150 --> 00:04:06.520
So, I'm going to go
ahead and read this.

00:04:06.520 --> 00:04:10.500
So, to celebrate Elizabeth
Bishop on her birthday,

00:04:10.500 --> 00:04:13.770
let's begin with a snippet
from one of her letters.

00:04:13.770 --> 00:04:18.330
Her witty, sharp, funny,
affectionate letters.

00:04:18.330 --> 00:04:24.410
It's a description of a remarkable
birthday present that she received

00:04:24.410 --> 00:04:27.770
at a party in Brazil, where
she was living at the time.

00:04:27.770 --> 00:04:31.790
She writes, "A neighbor
whom I scarcely know

00:04:31.790 --> 00:04:35.370
because we have no know
language in common for one thing,

00:04:35.370 --> 00:04:40.450
came bringing me my
lifelong dream, a Toucan.

00:04:40.450 --> 00:04:44.200
The woman, who gave him and her
husband, are Polish refugees

00:04:44.200 --> 00:04:46.580
and ran the zoo in Warsaw, I think.

00:04:46.580 --> 00:04:49.340
I never dreamed they'd
give me a Toucan.

00:04:49.340 --> 00:04:52.020
He eats six bananas a day.

00:04:52.020 --> 00:04:54.190
I must say, they seem to go
right through him and come

00:04:54.190 --> 00:04:57.330
out practically as good as new.

00:04:57.330 --> 00:05:00.970
Meat, grapes, to see him
swallowing grapes is rather

00:05:00.970 --> 00:05:02.890
like playing a pinball machine.

00:05:02.890 --> 00:05:05.410
And something I'd never known,

00:05:05.410 --> 00:05:09.120
they sleep with their tails
straight up over their heads.

00:05:09.120 --> 00:05:10.880
And their heads under a wing.

00:05:10.880 --> 00:05:14.710
So, the silhouette is just
like an inverted comma.

00:05:14.710 --> 00:05:18.730 position:56%
I am calling him Uncle Sam or Sammy.

00:05:18.730 --> 00:05:22.490
He steals everything,
particularly something bright.

00:05:22.490 --> 00:05:26.960
But so far the favorite toy
is a champagne bottle cork,

00:05:26.960 --> 00:05:29.850
also from the birthday."

00:05:29.850 --> 00:05:35.100
That story sounds just
like her, doesn't it?

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:39.380
The Polish refugees, who can't
communicate with her exactly

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:43.970
and whose sad story
she doesn't quite tell.

00:05:43.970 --> 00:05:48.220
The precise and strange
images, feeding the bird grapes

00:05:48.220 --> 00:05:50.350
like playing a pinball machine

00:05:50.350 --> 00:05:53.870
or his sleeping silhouette
like an inverted comma.

00:05:53.870 --> 00:05:57.270
And like the sandpiper
that famous Bishopy bird,

00:05:57.270 --> 00:06:03.150 position:56%
Sam also keeps his eye open, looking
for something, something, something.

00:06:03.150 --> 00:06:08.860
Something bright to steal from the
random, incoherence of the world.

00:06:08.860 --> 00:06:12.960
Other sources may call
Bishop's pet bird Sam, a parrot

00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:14.620
or say she named him in a moment

00:06:14.620 --> 00:06:18.810
of chauvinistic patriotism,
thus the Uncle Sam.

00:06:18.810 --> 00:06:21.580
But the story I choose
to believe is the one

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:23.960
that says Sam the Toucan's name,

00:06:23.960 --> 00:06:28.360
is an acronym for the three
qualities Elizabeth Bishop deemed

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:31.090
most important to a poem.

00:06:31.090 --> 00:06:41.260
Spontaneity, S, accuracy, A and
mystery, M. All or nearly all

00:06:41.260 --> 00:06:43.820
of her poems exhibit Samminess.

00:06:43.820 --> 00:06:45.550
But because it's one
of my favorites,

00:06:45.550 --> 00:06:48.560
let's look at the poem, "Poem."

00:06:48.560 --> 00:06:50.020
You know it, of course.

00:06:50.020 --> 00:06:52.310
It's an Ars Poetica of sorts,

00:06:52.310 --> 00:06:55.600
though Bishop would never
use so grand a title.

00:06:55.600 --> 00:07:02.070
Even Marianne Moore's poetry, is
a step too close to pontification.

00:07:02.070 --> 00:07:04.850
Bishop sticks with "Poem."

00:07:04.850 --> 00:07:07.220
It's up to us to generalize.

00:07:07.220 --> 00:07:11.710
She claims only that "Poem"
is a poem about a naÃ¯ve,

00:07:11.710 --> 00:07:14.550
that is unstudied painting.

00:07:14.550 --> 00:07:16.820
She doesn't claim, though we might,

00:07:16.820 --> 00:07:19.210
that "Poem" might have
something lasting

00:07:19.210 --> 00:07:22.230
to say about the art of poetry.

00:07:22.230 --> 00:07:27.090
So, let me read it to you.

00:07:27.090 --> 00:07:28.910
It's in geography three.

00:07:28.910 --> 00:07:35.020
You can see a copy of that up here.

00:07:35.020 --> 00:07:41.680
"Poem." "About the size of an
old-style dollar bill, American

00:07:41.680 --> 00:07:45.540
or Canadian, mostly the
same whites, gray greens,

00:07:45.540 --> 00:07:50.500 position:56%
and steel grays this little
painting, a sketch for a larger one?

00:07:50.500 --> 00:07:53.990
Has never earned any
money in its life.

00:07:53.990 --> 00:07:57.700
Useless and free, it
has spent seventy years

00:07:57.700 --> 00:08:02.700 position:56%
as a minor family relic handed along
collaterally to owners who looked

00:08:02.700 --> 00:08:05.110
at it sometimes, or
didn't bother to.

00:08:05.110 --> 00:08:11.870
It must be Nova Scotia; only there
does one see gabled wooden houses

00:08:11.870 --> 00:08:14.730
painted that awful shade of brown.

00:08:14.730 --> 00:08:18.570
The other houses, the
bits that show, are white.

00:08:18.570 --> 00:08:22.380
Elm trees, low hills, a
thin church steeple --

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:25.610
that gray-blue wisp -- or is it?

00:08:25.610 --> 00:08:29.890
In the foreground a water
meadow with some tiny cows,

00:08:29.890 --> 00:08:34.530
two brushstrokes each,
but confidently cows;

00:08:34.530 --> 00:08:38.760
two minuscule white geese in
the blue water, back-to-back,

00:08:38.760 --> 00:08:42.280
feeding, and a slanting stick.

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:46.310
Up closer, a wild iris,
white and yellow,

00:08:46.310 --> 00:08:49.750
fresh-squiggled from the tube.

00:08:49.750 --> 00:08:55.780
The air is fresh and cold; cold
early spring clear as gray glass;

00:08:55.780 --> 00:09:00.020
a half inch of blue sky below
the steel-gray storm clouds.

00:09:00.020 --> 00:09:02.220
They were the artist's specialty.

00:09:02.220 --> 00:09:05.910
A specklike bird is
flying to the left.

00:09:05.910 --> 00:09:10.370
Or is it a flyspeck
looking like a bird?

00:09:10.370 --> 00:09:16.030
Heavens, I recognize
the place, I know it!

00:09:16.030 --> 00:09:20.220
It's behind -- I can almost
remember the farmer's name.

00:09:20.220 --> 00:09:21.940
His barn backed on that meadow.

00:09:21.940 --> 00:09:27.140
There it is, titanium
white, one dab.

00:09:27.140 --> 00:09:32.510
The hint of steeple, filaments
of brush-hairs, barely there,

00:09:32.510 --> 00:09:34.860
must be the Presbyterian church.

00:09:34.860 --> 00:09:37.610
Would that be Miss
Gillespie's house?

00:09:37.610 --> 00:09:43.150
Those particular geese and cows
are naturally before my time.

00:09:43.150 --> 00:09:47.850
A sketch done in an hour,
"in one breath," once taken

00:09:47.850 --> 00:09:50.840
from a trunk and handed over.

00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:52.140
Would you like this?

00:09:52.140 --> 00:09:54.680
I'll never have room to
hang these things again.

00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:58.070
Your Uncle George, no,
mine, my Uncle George,

00:09:58.070 --> 00:10:01.090
he'd be your great-uncle,
left them all with Mother

00:10:01.090 --> 00:10:02.390
when he went back to England.

00:10:02.390 --> 00:10:09.260
You know, he was quite famous,
an R.A. I never knew him.

00:10:09.260 --> 00:10:14.110 position:56%
We both knew this place, apparently,
this literal small backwater,

00:10:14.110 --> 00:10:19.250
looked at it long enough to
memorize it, our years apart.

00:10:19.250 --> 00:10:21.650
How strange.

00:10:21.650 --> 00:10:24.530
And it's still loved,
or its memory is.

00:10:24.530 --> 00:10:26.630
It must have changed a lot.

00:10:26.630 --> 00:10:30.740
Our visions coincided --
"visions" is too serious a word --

00:10:30.740 --> 00:10:37.430
our looks, two looks: art "copying
from life" and life itself,

00:10:37.430 --> 00:10:39.660
life and the memory of it

00:10:39.660 --> 00:10:43.310
so compressed they've
turned into each other.

00:10:43.310 --> 00:10:45.190
Which is which?

00:10:45.190 --> 00:10:50.860
Life and the memory of it cramped,
dim, on a piece of Bristol board,

00:10:50.860 --> 00:10:55.450
dim, but how live, how
touching in detail.

00:10:55.450 --> 00:11:00.810
The little that we get for free,
the little of our earthly trust.

00:11:00.810 --> 00:11:06.240
Not much. About the size of
our abidance along with theirs:

00:11:06.240 --> 00:11:10.820
the munching cows, the
iris, crisp and shivering,

00:11:10.820 --> 00:11:14.710
the water still standing
from spring freshets,

00:11:14.710 --> 00:11:19.000
the yet-to-be-dismantled
elms, the geese."

00:11:27.730 --> 00:11:31.690
So, I'm going to look
at those Sam qualities.

00:11:33.820 --> 00:11:37.960 position:56%
Spontaneity is everywhere in "Poem."

00:11:37.960 --> 00:11:42.130
The voice that speaks the
poem is itself as alive

00:11:42.130 --> 00:11:46.680
as that shivering Iris, fresh
squiggled from the tube.

00:11:46.680 --> 00:11:51.760
As the speaker stops
and starts, asserts

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:55.100
and qualifies her assertions,
shifting in tone

00:11:55.100 --> 00:11:59.330
from the parenthetical
aside, to the exclamatory.

00:11:59.330 --> 00:12:04.460 position:56%
From a collage bit of reported
dialogue, to a meditation on memory,

00:12:04.460 --> 00:12:07.630
time and the intimacies of art.

00:12:07.630 --> 00:12:13.670
We feel as though we are hearing a
real person talking in real time.

00:12:13.670 --> 00:12:18.060
As if she's just there across
the table chatting with us.

00:12:18.060 --> 00:12:20.170
It's not chat, of course.

00:12:20.170 --> 00:12:23.050
Not tossed off or partially
considered.

00:12:23.050 --> 00:12:28.000
The poet has revised and revised,
toward that illusion of casual,

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.410
off the cuff, in one
breath naturalness.

00:12:32.410 --> 00:12:36.020
It's an artificially
created naturalness.

00:12:36.020 --> 00:12:41.370
And artfully rehearsed spontaneity,
"Heavens, I recognized the place,

00:12:41.370 --> 00:12:47.010
I know it," the speaker says,
as if she had just then realized

00:12:47.010 --> 00:12:49.930
and is just now telling us.

00:12:49.930 --> 00:12:55.970
A just then, that happens over and
over, every time you read the poem.

00:12:55.970 --> 00:13:02.610
Hers is a spontaneity that endures
in the language of the poem.

00:13:02.610 --> 00:13:07.340
The next Sam quality, accuracy,
isn't just about sticking

00:13:07.340 --> 00:13:11.150
to the facts, although Bishop
rarely veers from fact,

00:13:11.150 --> 00:13:15.080
in order to find some
kind of capital T, truth.

00:13:15.080 --> 00:13:18.550
Is there any such thing,
she might ask?

00:13:18.550 --> 00:13:21.170
Her idea of accuracy isn't only

00:13:21.170 --> 00:13:24.840
about the honest admission
of ugliness either.

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:26.500
"That awful shade of brown,"

00:13:26.500 --> 00:13:31.280
she says about her
beloved Nova Scotia houses.

00:13:31.280 --> 00:13:35.110
Nor is her accuracy only
for recalled details

00:13:35.110 --> 00:13:37.580
like Miss Gillespie's
name or the size

00:13:37.580 --> 00:13:41.000 position:56%
of American versus Canadian dollars.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:47.400
Bishop's accuracy isn't about
verisimilitude or realism, per say.

00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:53.110 position:56%
Although, sometimes a sort of
magnified, super realism may result.

00:13:53.110 --> 00:13:56.970
Her sort of accuracy is
in inherent in her precise

00:13:56.970 --> 00:14:00.010
and uncannily strange images.

00:14:00.010 --> 00:14:03.810
A Toucan posed like an
inverted comma, say.

00:14:03.810 --> 00:14:09.750 position:56%
Or this passage in poem, "A
specklike bird is flying to the left

00:14:09.750 --> 00:14:14.400
or is it a flyspeck
looking like a bird?"

00:14:14.400 --> 00:14:18.580
These are accurate images
that show, in their accuracy,

00:14:18.580 --> 00:14:23.270
how weird the ordinary actually is.

00:14:23.270 --> 00:14:25.370
The size of things shifts

00:14:25.370 --> 00:14:29.800
as that famous magnifying
eye finds its focus.

00:14:29.800 --> 00:14:34.790
A bird as tall and colorful as the
family size box of Froot Loops,

00:14:34.790 --> 00:14:38.400
is compared to a tiny black comma.

00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:42.770
A painted gull, is compared
to a flying speck or a speck

00:14:42.770 --> 00:14:47.280
of fly is mistaken
for a laughing gull.

00:14:47.280 --> 00:14:52.690 position:56%
In the precision and de-familiarized
strangeness of her images, "Heavens,

00:14:52.690 --> 00:14:57.250
I recognize the thing," our
perspective shifts and aware

00:14:57.250 --> 00:15:01.050
of our looking, we see with
sudden vividness and accuracy.

00:15:01.050 --> 00:15:05.750 position:56%
Although, sometimes the view is like
the one a suddenly giant Alice saw

00:15:05.750 --> 00:15:07.570
through the wonderland keyhole.

00:15:07.570 --> 00:15:13.720
Or the one we see through the glass
in a Joseph Cornell assemblage.

00:15:13.720 --> 00:15:17.750
Bishop loved both, by the
way, Alice and Cornell.

00:15:17.750 --> 00:15:21.930
Sometimes her realism, as with
the trompe-l'oeil flyspeck,

00:15:21.930 --> 00:15:29.450 position:56%
asks us to question the real, at the
same time as it seems represent it.

00:15:29.450 --> 00:15:35.520 position:56%
The last of the Sam the Toucan triad
of key poetic qualities is mystery.

00:15:35.520 --> 00:15:38.080
The one hardest to describe.

00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:41.680
But here's what I think it isn't.

00:15:41.680 --> 00:15:45.950
It isn't the dark murkiness
of imprecision.

00:15:45.950 --> 00:15:49.930
Or an answer withheld
until the who done it ends.

00:15:49.930 --> 00:15:54.210
Or some deep hidden meaning,
set down in Spark Notes.

00:15:54.210 --> 00:15:57.540
Bishop's mystery isn't
knowledge obscured

00:15:57.540 --> 00:15:59.900
or withheld from us readers.

00:15:59.900 --> 00:16:04.140
It's not as something added
either, like a grating of nutmeg.

