00:33:38.500 --> 00:33:40.570
the commitment to prose order.

00:33:40.570 --> 00:33:43.250
All of those things I was
picking up because that was a time

00:33:43.250 --> 00:33:46.490
when I was living in Oregon
when I was trying to make myself

00:33:46.490 --> 00:33:49.910
into a poet, along with all
the other things I was doing.

00:33:49.910 --> 00:33:53.600
And you know and then I
came across this poem.

00:33:53.600 --> 00:34:03.880
And I realized that this person
who I thought was, you know,

00:34:03.880 --> 00:34:11.760
a model of a certain kind of
literary virtue and a certain kind

00:34:11.760 --> 00:34:19.590 position:56%
of clarity and simplicity and order,

00:34:19.590 --> 00:34:24.730
was actually an incredibly
dramatically ambitions poet.

00:34:24.730 --> 00:34:27.150 position:56%
And I'll read "In the Waiting Room."

00:34:27.150 --> 00:34:31.430
And then I will read kind

00:34:31.430 --> 00:34:36.730
of its companion poem,
"At the Fish Houses."

00:34:36.730 --> 00:34:41.600
And this is the first
poem in "Geography Three."

00:34:41.600 --> 00:34:44.180
"In the Waiting Room."

00:34:45.240 --> 00:34:48.780
"In Worcester, Massachusetts,
I went with Aunt Consuelo

00:34:48.780 --> 00:34:52.940
to keep her dentist's appointment
and sat and waited for her

00:34:52.940 --> 00:34:55.580
in the dentist's waiting room.

00:34:55.580 --> 00:34:57.020
It was winter.

00:34:57.020 --> 00:34:59.220
It got dark early.

00:34:59.220 --> 00:35:03.190
The waiting room was full
of grown-up people, arctics

00:35:03.190 --> 00:35:06.870
and overcoats, lamps and magazines.

00:35:06.870 --> 00:35:11.440
My aunt was inside what seemed
like a long time and while I waited

00:35:11.440 --> 00:35:14.340
and read the National Geographic.

00:35:14.340 --> 00:35:16.090
I could read.

00:35:16.090 --> 00:35:19.160
And carefully studied
the photographs:

00:35:19.160 --> 00:35:24.290
the inside of a volcano, black, and
full of ashes; then it was spilling

00:35:24.290 --> 00:35:26.840
over in rivulets of fire.

00:35:26.840 --> 00:35:30.890
Osa and Martin Johnson
dressed in riding breeches,

00:35:30.890 --> 00:35:34.400
laced boots, and pith helmets.

00:35:34.400 --> 00:35:40.580
A dead man slung on a pole
"Long Pig," the caption said.

00:35:40.580 --> 00:35:45.680
Babies with pointed heads wound
round and round with string; black,

00:35:45.680 --> 00:35:49.900
naked women with necks wound
round and round with wire

00:35:49.900 --> 00:35:52.830
like the necks of light bulbs.

00:35:52.830 --> 00:35:55.840
Their breasts were horrifying.

00:35:55.840 --> 00:35:58.100
I read it right straight through.

00:35:58.100 --> 00:36:00.470
I was too shy to stop.

00:36:00.470 --> 00:36:08.030
And then I looked at the cover:
the yellow margins, the date.

00:36:08.030 --> 00:36:13.040
Suddenly, from inside, came an oh!

00:36:13.040 --> 00:36:20.620
of pain, Aunt Consuelo's
voice not very loud or long.

00:36:20.620 --> 00:36:24.530
I wasn't at all surprised; even
then I knew she was a foolish,

00:36:24.530 --> 00:36:25.980
timid woman.

00:36:25.980 --> 00:36:30.490
I might have been embarrassed,
but wasn't.

00:36:30.490 --> 00:36:34.510
What took me completely
by surprise was

00:36:34.510 --> 00:36:40.370
that it was me: my
voice, in my mouth.

00:36:40.370 --> 00:36:46.680
Without thinking at all I
was my foolish aunt, I-- we--

00:36:46.680 --> 00:36:51.190
were falling, falling, our
eyes glued to the cover

00:36:51.190 --> 00:36:56.940
of the National Geographic,
February, 1918.

00:36:57.990 --> 00:37:03.650
I said to myself: three days
and you'll be seven years old.

00:37:03.650 --> 00:37:06.080
I was saying it to
stop the sensation

00:37:06.080 --> 00:37:09.090
of falling off the
round, turning world.

00:37:09.090 --> 00:37:11.940
Into cold, blue-black space.

00:37:11.940 --> 00:37:18.880
But I felt: you are an I, you are
an Elizabeth, you are one of them.

00:37:18.880 --> 00:37:21.410
Why should you be one, too?

00:37:21.410 --> 00:37:27.040
I scarcely dared to look
to see what it was I was.

00:37:27.040 --> 00:37:30.840
I gave a sidelong glance --
I couldn't look any higher --

00:37:30.840 --> 00:37:36.490 position:56%
at shadowy gray knees, trousers and
skirts and boots and different pairs

00:37:36.490 --> 00:37:39.640
of hands lying under the lamps.

00:37:39.640 --> 00:37:42.700
I knew that nothing
stranger had ever happened,

00:37:42.700 --> 00:37:45.760
that nothing stranger
could ever happen.

00:37:45.760 --> 00:37:50.530
Why should I be my
aunt, or me, or anyone?

00:37:50.530 --> 00:37:56.840
What similarities boots, hands, the
family voice I felt in my throat,

00:37:56.840 --> 00:37:59.040
or even the National Geographic

00:37:59.040 --> 00:38:03.790
and those awful hanging
breasts held us all together

00:38:03.790 --> 00:38:06.840
or made us all just one?

00:38:06.840 --> 00:38:13.010
How I didn't know any word
for it how "unlikely".

00:38:13.010 --> 00:38:19.080
How had I come to be here, like
them, and overhear a cry of pain

00:38:19.080 --> 00:38:23.790
that could have got loud
and worse but hadn't?

00:38:23.790 --> 00:38:26.720
The waiting room was
bright and too hot.

00:38:26.720 --> 00:38:33.670
It was sliding beneath a big
black wave, another, and another.

00:38:33.670 --> 00:38:36.050
Then I was back in it.

00:38:36.050 --> 00:38:38.030
The War was on.

00:38:38.030 --> 00:38:42.640
Outside, in Worcester,
Massachusetts, were night and slush

00:38:42.640 --> 00:38:48.000
and cold, and it was still
the fifth of February, 1918."

00:39:04.590 --> 00:39:11.930
So, that is about that moment of
recognition, that moment of being.

00:39:15.090 --> 00:39:21.470
That we arrive and arrive and
arrive at and always, you know,

00:39:23.020 --> 00:39:28.440
seem to slip past at the
moment of our arrival.

00:39:28.440 --> 00:39:30.620
And it's interesting,
at the end of her life,

00:39:30.620 --> 00:39:33.630
she goes back to that experience.

00:39:35.460 --> 00:39:40.730
Which is sort of -- and she
frames it in an interesting way.

00:39:40.730 --> 00:39:44.270
She frames it in the
context of herself.

00:39:44.270 --> 00:39:47.420
Because that experience
has many facets.

00:39:47.420 --> 00:39:52.900
And you know often when you look at
Bishop as a whole, you tend to sort

00:39:52.900 --> 00:39:57.430
of see her as a --
either a Christian poet

00:39:57.430 --> 00:40:01.160
in a post Christian world or a
post Christian poet, you know,

00:40:01.160 --> 00:40:03.530 position:56%
still laboring in a Christian world.

00:40:03.530 --> 00:40:08.010
And there's kind of that constant
tension, that doubling of her sort

00:40:08.010 --> 00:40:10.180
of spiritual consciousness.

00:40:10.180 --> 00:40:19.160 position:56%
And you know and at the end of her
life she seems to have freed herself

00:40:19.160 --> 00:40:22.590
from the contradictions
that sort of defined

00:40:22.590 --> 00:40:26.200
and fructified her
poetry throughout its,

00:40:26.200 --> 00:40:28.540
you know, flowering in her life.

00:40:28.540 --> 00:40:30.760
And just gets back

00:40:30.760 --> 00:40:37.740
to an irresolvable existential
core and dilemma, you know.

00:40:37.740 --> 00:40:41.430
And that is not really true about
the middle part of her career.

00:40:41.430 --> 00:40:48.220
It's sort of -- that question
isn't sort of reducible.

00:40:48.220 --> 00:40:52.390
That question of being, isn't
reducible in the middle part

00:40:52.390 --> 00:40:57.030
of her career, to merely the
existential condition of the South,

00:40:57.030 --> 00:41:03.230
but has all of this sort of
doctrinal fullness to it.

00:41:03.230 --> 00:41:06.420
And an example of that is the
next poem I'm going to read

00:41:06.420 --> 00:41:11.130
"At the Fishhouses,"
which is sort of --

00:41:11.130 --> 00:41:13.060
you know, I guess in a
way the companion poem

00:41:13.060 --> 00:41:16.240
to "In the Waiting
Room" in some way.

00:41:16.240 --> 00:41:22.610
And you know, I mean, I
think she tends to sort

00:41:22.610 --> 00:41:28.640
of recycle motifs throughout
her career because --

00:41:28.640 --> 00:41:30.090
well, for one reason
because she worked

00:41:30.090 --> 00:41:31.830
on poems for so long, you know.

00:41:31.830 --> 00:41:34.000
I mean, I think "The Moose" was

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:36.920
around for twenty-five years
before it got finished.

00:41:36.920 --> 00:41:41.420
I think it's late nineteen
forty-eight that she takes that,

00:41:41.420 --> 00:41:46.230
you know, that bus ride
that "The Moose" describes.

00:41:46.230 --> 00:41:50.460
And she doesn't publish that poem
until the nineteen seventies.

00:41:50.460 --> 00:41:58.820
So, there's a kind of constant
return to certain ideas and themes,

00:41:58.820 --> 00:42:01.580
which reflects a sort
of a temporal reality

00:42:01.580 --> 00:42:03.560
in which she was always living.

00:42:03.560 --> 00:42:06.060
So, kind of really interesting.

00:42:06.060 --> 00:42:09.430
And I think even "Poem" has a --

00:42:09.430 --> 00:42:13.560
I think that painting is actually
mentioned earlier in her work.

00:42:13.560 --> 00:42:15.720
I can't remember exactly
where it is now,

00:42:15.720 --> 00:42:19.660
but you know that painting
comes back again at the end.

00:42:19.660 --> 00:42:23.020
So, it's sort of, you know.

00:42:23.020 --> 00:42:29.140
And this is sort of the theme of
"In the Waiting Room," conceived

00:42:29.140 --> 00:42:32.330
and understood from a different
point of view entirely.

00:42:32.330 --> 00:42:34.850
"At the Fishhouses."

00:42:36.190 --> 00:42:38.830
"Although it is a cold evening,

00:42:38.830 --> 00:42:44.390
down by one of the fishhouses an
old man sits netting, his net,

00:42:44.390 --> 00:42:48.930
in the gloaming almost
invisible, a dark purple-brown,

00:42:48.930 --> 00:42:51.830
and his shuttle worn and polished.

00:42:51.830 --> 00:42:55.960
The air smells so strong of
codfish it makes one's nose run

00:42:55.960 --> 00:42:58.360
and one's eyes water.

00:42:58.360 --> 00:43:03.240
The five fishhouses have
steeply peaked roofs and narrow,

00:43:03.240 --> 00:43:08.230
cleated gangplanks slant up
to storerooms in the gables

00:43:08.230 --> 00:43:12.330
for the wheelbarrows to
be pushed up and down on.

00:43:12.330 --> 00:43:17.670
All is silver: the heavy surface
of the sea, swelling slowly

00:43:17.670 --> 00:43:22.380
as if considering spilling
over, is opaque, but the silver

00:43:22.380 --> 00:43:25.180
of the benches, the
lobster pots, and masts,

00:43:25.180 --> 00:43:28.160
scattered among the
wild jagged rocks,

00:43:28.160 --> 00:43:32.540
is of an apparent translucence
like the small old buildings

00:43:32.540 --> 00:43:37.580
with an emerald moss growing
on their shoreward walls.

00:43:37.580 --> 00:43:41.570
The big fish tubs are
completely lined with layers

00:43:41.570 --> 00:43:47.420 position:56%
of beautiful herring scales and the
wheelbarrows are similarly plastered

00:43:47.420 --> 00:43:51.050
with creamy iridescent
coats of mail,

00:43:51.050 --> 00:43:55.680
with small iridescent
flies crawling on them.

00:43:55.680 --> 00:43:59.020
Up on the little slope
behind the houses,

00:43:59.020 --> 00:44:04.720 position:56%
set in the sparse bright sprinkle of
grass, is an ancient wooden capstan,

00:44:04.720 --> 00:44:09.770
cracked, with two long bleached
handles and some melancholy stains,

00:44:09.770 --> 00:44:15.120
like dried blood, where
the ironwork has rusted.

00:44:15.120 --> 00:44:18.340
The old man accepts a Lucky Strike.

00:44:18.340 --> 00:44:21.270
He was a friend of my grandfather.

00:44:21.270 --> 00:44:25.080
We talk of the decline in
the population and of codfish

00:44:25.080 --> 00:44:29.430
and herring while he waits
for a herring boat to come in.

00:44:29.430 --> 00:44:32.950
There are sequins on his
vest and on his thumb.

00:44:32.950 --> 00:44:36.540
He has scraped the scales,
the principal beauty,

00:44:36.540 --> 00:44:40.350
from unnumbered fish with
that black old knife,

00:44:40.350 --> 00:44:43.420
the blade of which
is almost worn away.

00:44:43.420 --> 00:44:49.490
Down at the water's edge, at the
place where they haul up the boats,

00:44:49.490 --> 00:44:52.920
up the long ramp descending
into the water,

00:44:52.920 --> 00:44:59.180 position:56%
thin silver tree trunks are laid
horizontally across the gray stones,

00:44:59.180 --> 00:45:06.050
down and down at intervals
of four or five feet.

00:45:06.050 --> 00:45:11.570
Cold dark deep and absolutely
clear, element bearable

00:45:11.570 --> 00:45:16.240
to no mortal, to fish and to seals.

00:45:16.240 --> 00:45:22.050
One seal particularly I have
seen here evening after evening.

00:45:22.050 --> 00:45:24.720
He was curious about me.

00:45:24.720 --> 00:45:31.550
He was interested in music; like
me a believer in total immersion,

00:45:31.550 --> 00:45:34.730 position:56%
so I used to sing him Baptist hymns.

00:45:34.730 --> 00:45:39.360
I also sang "A Mighty
Fortress Is Our God."

00:45:39.360 --> 00:45:43.230
He stood up in the water
and regarded me steadily,

00:45:43.230 --> 00:45:45.460
moving his head a little.

00:45:45.460 --> 00:45:49.340
Then he would disappear,
then suddenly emerge almost

00:45:49.340 --> 00:45:53.400
in the same spot, with a
sort of shrug as if it were

00:45:53.400 --> 00:45:56.630
against his better judgment.

00:45:56.630 --> 00:46:02.720
Cold dark deep and absolutely
clear, the clear gray icy water.

00:46:02.720 --> 00:46:07.090
Back, behind us, the
dignified tall firs begin.

00:46:07.090 --> 00:46:10.340
Bluish, associating
with their shadows,

00:46:10.340 --> 00:46:14.580
a million Christmas trees
stand waiting for Christmas.

00:46:14.580 --> 00:46:20.620
The water seems suspended above the
rounded gray and blue-gray stones.

00:46:20.620 --> 00:46:25.830
I have seen it over and over,
the same sea, the same, slightly,

00:46:25.830 --> 00:46:32.240 position:56%
indifferently swinging above the
stones, icily free above the stones,

00:46:32.240 --> 00:46:34.940 position:56%
above the stones and then the world.

00:46:34.940 --> 00:46:38.800
If you should dip your hand in,
your wrist would ache immediately,

00:46:38.800 --> 00:46:41.970
your bones would begin to
ache and your hand would burn

00:46:41.970 --> 00:46:46.970 position:56%
as if the water were a transmutation
of fire that feeds on stones

00:46:46.970 --> 00:46:50.120
and burns with a dark gray flame.

00:46:50.120 --> 00:46:54.980
If you tasted it, it would
first taste bitter, then briny,

00:46:54.980 --> 00:46:57.950
then surely burn your tongue.

00:46:57.950 --> 00:47:04.420 position:56%
It is like what we imagine knowledge
to be: dark, salt, clear, moving,

00:47:04.420 --> 00:47:09.790
utterly free, drawn from the
cold hard mouth of the world,

00:47:09.790 --> 00:47:15.460
derived from the rocky breasts
forever, flowing and drawn,

00:47:15.460 --> 00:47:21.000
and since our knowledge is
historical, flowing, and flown."

00:47:35.200 --> 00:47:40.550
She always starts out so
low, so even, you know.

00:47:40.550 --> 00:47:46.240 position:56%
It's just kind of a -- and you never
quite realize how much pressure is

00:47:46.240 --> 00:47:47.540
building up.

00:47:47.540 --> 00:47:50.550
Because the control is
so magnificent, you know,

00:47:50.550 --> 00:47:54.580
the kind of -- the
mastery of the sentence.

00:47:54.580 --> 00:47:58.500
The commitment to like living
the poem along the sentence

00:47:58.500 --> 00:48:01.840
and seeing its opportunities
and expanding it outward,

00:48:01.840 --> 00:48:05.900
but at the same time, there is
this other narrative taking place

00:48:05.900 --> 00:48:11.570
in her mind that, you know, of
which we are just getting tiny

00:48:11.570 --> 00:48:12.870
little glimpses.

00:48:12.870 --> 00:48:15.920
You know, we don't quite
understand what's going on,

00:48:15.920 --> 00:48:21.000
but the way in which she sort of
continually shepherds us, you know,

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:23.180
further and further and further.

00:48:23.180 --> 00:48:25.290
Until she can't go
any further, you know.

00:48:25.290 --> 00:48:27.710
I mean, in some sense,
she kind of always arrives

00:48:27.710 --> 00:48:30.230
at a limit that's fundamental
in some way I think.

00:48:30.230 --> 00:48:32.670
And you know I think one of the --

00:48:32.670 --> 00:48:37.900
you know, I think a part of it has
always, when I've contemplated her.

00:48:37.900 --> 00:48:40.240
And of course, I've
contemplated her a lot.

00:48:40.240 --> 00:48:48.490
She was a poet who freed
me, along with Auden.

00:48:48.490 --> 00:48:55.730
When I was kind of in my sort
of early and mid-twenties,

00:48:55.730 --> 00:49:00.740 position:56%
freed me from the terrible burden of
having to write like John Ashbery.

00:49:00.740 --> 00:49:04.110
Because he was sort of,
like, when I was a kid,

00:49:04.110 --> 00:49:07.720
I was a hip young poetry
reader and literature reader.

00:49:07.720 --> 00:49:09.610
And Ashbery was really cool.

00:49:09.610 --> 00:49:13.260
This was, like, before
"Self-Portrait in a Convex Mirror"

00:49:13.260 --> 00:49:16.470
when he was sort of a
New York coterie figure.

00:49:16.470 --> 00:49:21.000 position:56%
And all the hip literary kids I knew
came from New York and they listened

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:23.240
to "The Velvet Underground"
and they read John Ashbery.

00:49:23.240 --> 00:49:24.800 position:56%
And I thought I had to be like them,

00:49:24.800 --> 00:49:27.210
but I couldn't quite
be like them, you know.

00:49:27.210 --> 00:49:31.860 position:56%
And but I recognized the distinction
of someone like Ashbery and I sort

00:49:31.860 --> 00:49:35.170
of felt, well, you know, I
had to find another model.

00:49:35.170 --> 00:49:37.340
And Bishop came along and
she was really a lifeline

00:49:37.340 --> 00:49:38.950
for me in that way, you know.

00:49:38.950 --> 00:49:46.230
And I sort of felt, like, oh, yeah,
you know, this is really great.

00:49:46.230 --> 00:49:49.050
And it seems in some
way unmarked by time.

00:49:49.050 --> 00:49:50.660
It seems like there seems

00:49:50.660 --> 00:49:53.790
to be something perennial
about these concerns.

00:49:53.790 --> 00:49:55.970
They will always be
the same concerns.

00:49:55.970 --> 00:49:57.270
There's some -- seems

00:49:57.270 --> 00:50:06.170
to be something absolutely
eternal about the allegiance.

00:50:06.170 --> 00:50:08.900
You know, the allegiance
to language at this level.

00:50:08.900 --> 00:50:13.380
The kind of recognition that
language is sort of a living thing

00:50:13.380 --> 00:50:16.620
and you have to get out of its way
and let it do what it should do.

00:50:16.620 --> 00:50:20.840
And then, you know, the
commitment to the world,

00:50:20.840 --> 00:50:25.510
especially the visual world.

00:50:25.510 --> 00:50:31.880
And the yeah, there's
something beyond these kind

00:50:31.880 --> 00:50:34.890
of games we're playing.

00:50:34.890 --> 00:50:39.300
And also I think there's
a kind of historicity too

00:50:39.300 --> 00:50:45.840
because Bishop was never -- she
never abandoned the romantic ode.

00:50:45.840 --> 00:50:49.610
You know, she's like kind of
the person of her generation

00:50:49.610 --> 00:50:56.980
who continued to write them, after
people like Roethke and Lowell

00:50:56.980 --> 00:51:02.130 position:56%
and Berryman sort of let them go and
started trying to do something else.

00:51:02.130 --> 00:51:06.390
She was kind of committed to that,
you know, to that great series

00:51:06.390 --> 00:51:10.770
of poems that begin, you know, in
the seventeen nineties and move

00:51:10.770 --> 00:51:12.180
up to her and she managed them.

00:51:12.180 --> 00:51:15.510
She managed them very beautifully.

00:51:15.510 --> 00:51:19.180
So, she was very important to me
and it's great to come down here

00:51:19.180 --> 00:51:24.650
and sort of be allowed to
celebrate her, you know

00:51:24.650 --> 00:51:28.330
and thank her in some way.

00:51:28.330 --> 00:51:29.910
Well, she's dead and gone.

00:51:29.910 --> 00:51:34.580
She's not listening to
us, I'm sure, positive.

00:51:34.580 --> 00:51:41.690
Anyway, I'm going to read a poem
of mine and which is a recent poem.

00:51:41.690 --> 00:51:52.980
And I guess it's sort of -- it's
Bishop-like in a lot of ways,

00:51:52.980 --> 00:51:57.050
but it's also a celebration
of sight.

00:51:57.050 --> 00:52:06.000 position:56%
And it's a poem about my mother, who
is very old and kind of, you know

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:12.650
and in distressed physical
condition now.

00:52:13.960 --> 00:52:19.580
And she also is, like Bishop,
is a strong and scrutable woman.

00:52:19.580 --> 00:52:22.670
The poem is called,
"Your Living Eyes."

00:52:24.940 --> 00:52:28.530
They wheeled you, your caregivers
did, to the picture window

00:52:28.530 --> 00:52:31.360
to watch the birds
fretting at the feeder.

00:52:31.360 --> 00:52:35.330
Then they forgot you
there and you forgot them.

00:52:35.330 --> 00:52:39.180
A thousand years later, the
angel of death sidled in,

00:52:39.180 --> 00:52:41.610
disguised as a little girl.

00:52:41.610 --> 00:52:46.420
Clutching at her pinafore and
chewing the ends of her pigtails.

00:52:46.420 --> 00:52:50.570
She had a look whose
vacancy was over rehearsed.

00:52:50.570 --> 00:52:54.410
But I hear your interview
with her went well.

00:52:54.410 --> 00:52:56.900 position:56%
I hear actually, that it went better

00:52:56.900 --> 00:53:00.430
than anybody could
ever thought it would.

00:53:00.430 --> 00:53:05.970
She said, "beauty and
sadness are never far apart."

00:53:05.970 --> 00:53:09.010
You said, "bullshit."

00:53:09.010 --> 00:53:16.310 position:56%
She said, "some birds are real, some
are invisible, but which are which?"

00:53:16.310 --> 00:53:19.940
You said, "back off, bitch."

00:53:19.940 --> 00:53:22.410
She stared out the window.

00:53:22.410 --> 00:53:26.080
Her eyes narrowed,
but they didn't touch.

00:53:26.080 --> 00:53:28.050
What was she seeing?

00:53:28.050 --> 00:53:31.550
What was she saying to herself?

00:53:31.550 --> 00:53:35.400
Do I know or do I care?

00:53:35.400 --> 00:53:38.530
Enough with these impassive forces.

00:53:38.530 --> 00:53:40.930
This one or that other one,

00:53:40.930 --> 00:53:46.070
the one who gave you life,
you, who gave me life.

00:53:46.070 --> 00:53:49.540
The yellow of the finches
is as molten as ever,

00:53:49.540 --> 00:53:52.320
splashing on the holly bushes.

00:53:52.320 --> 00:53:57.910 position:56%
The moon, pale white inside the pale
blue morning, dropping its panicles

00:53:57.910 --> 00:54:02.330
of glass on the bright
grass, is climbing up.

00:54:02.330 --> 00:54:05.420
But the sun is climbing down.

00:54:05.420 --> 00:54:10.250
The world your eyes see is
the world as it really is.

00:54:10.250 --> 00:54:14.040
And you and I are going
to live in it forever.

00:54:14.040 --> 00:54:18.190
And we will hitchhike to
the painted hills together

00:54:18.190 --> 00:54:20.440
and hop a freight back home."

00:54:20.440 --> 00:54:23.510
Thank you.

